(window.webpackJsonp=window.webpackJsonp||[]).push([[89],{310:function(e){e.exports={data:{posts:{totalCount:78,pageInfo:{totalPages:8,currentPage:6,isFirst:!1,isLast:!1},edges:[{node:{title:"Raspberry Pi Project 2 - Car-ing it",image:null,path:"/blog/2015/06/23/raspberry-pi-project-2-car-ing-it",excerpt:"<p>Hey IGNers!</p>\n",date:"2015-06-23T00:00:00.000Z",timeToRead:1}},{node:{title:"Raspberry Pi 2 powered Arcade",image:"/media/images/blog/PiGloryShot.jpg",path:"/blog/2015/04/22/raspberry-pi-2-powered-arcade",excerpt:"<p>For a while now I've been wanting to do a project with the Raspberry Pi. The ultra low cost, single board computer is making roads in both education and the do-it-yourself maker scene. It's a great platform to learn programming and basic electronics, and the heart of many enthusiast projects. After thinking about what I could make, I settled on an emulation-based arcade machine.</p>\n",date:"2015-04-22T00:00:00.000Z",timeToRead:8}},{node:{title:"Retronauts Advanced",image:null,path:"/blog/2013/03/27/retronauts-advanced",excerpt:"<p>Just as 1UP fades into darkness, part of its legacy lives on thanks to its fans. The Kickstarter campaign for Retronauts has really taken off, having reached its goal within a few hours and now has over four times what it asked for with 24 days still remaining.</p>\n",date:"2013-03-27T00:00:00.000Z",timeToRead:1}},{node:{title:"Backwards compatibility on all PS3s?",image:null,path:"/blog/2013/03/21/backwards-compatibility-on-all-p-s3s",excerpt:"<p>Recently, reverse engineers and hackers have been able to extract the file used for PSN distributed Playstation 2 classics titles. Contrary to popular belief, these games are not reprogrammed ports of the games to the Playstation 3, but are complete emulations of the unmodified original game. Smart people have been able to implement this to allow the Sony designed emulator to run an extensive library of Playstation 2 games.</p>\n",date:"2013-03-21T00:00:00.000Z",timeToRead:1}},{node:{title:"Backwards compatibility and IGN",image:null,path:"/blog/2013/03/08/backwards-compatibility-and-ign",excerpt:"\n",date:"2013-03-08T00:00:00.000Z",timeToRead:1}},{node:{title:"PS4 Backwards Compatibility: Offered by a peripheral?",image:"/media/images/blog/backcompat.png",path:"/blog/2013/03/03/p-s4-backwards-compatibility-offered-by-a-peripheral",excerpt:"<p>Backwards compatibility is a feature consumers might assume is available. Other than the Playstation 3, every video game console and handheld released since 2002 has offered it. Every smartphone or computer has it. Even when Apple switched processor architecture from PowerPC to Intel's x86 in 2006,Â  they designed the Rosetta software to allow older programs to work in the new systems.</p>\n",date:"2013-03-03T00:00:00.000Z",timeToRead:2}},{node:{title:"Being on IGN",image:null,path:"/blog/2013/03/01/being-on-ign",excerpt:"<p>With all the talk and recent happenings with IGN being purchased by Ziff Davis, things that I have often pondered have been brought to the forefront.</p>\n",date:"2013-03-01T00:00:00.000Z",timeToRead:3}},{node:{title:"8 reasons for backwards compatibility",image:"/media/images/blog/gta.jpg",path:"/blog/2013/02/27/8-reasons-for-backwards-compatibility",excerpt:'<p>At the recent Playstation event it was announced that Sony is moving to a new architecture with the Playstation 4, making it lack all backwards compatibility with current generation titles. On the fabulous and popular <a href="http://feeds.ign.com/ignfeeds/podcasts/beyond/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">Podcast Beyond</a>, the dream team aren\'t concerned about this, saying that backwards compatibility isn\'t a feature they want or that many people will use.</p>\n',date:"2013-02-27T00:00:00.000Z",timeToRead:3}},{node:{title:"Uncle Ziff",image:null,path:"/blog/2013/02/23/uncle-ziff",excerpt:"<p>Things I liked and regularly used that Ziff Davis sold off, drastically downsized or outright killed:</p>\n",date:"2013-02-23T00:00:00.000Z",timeToRead:1}},{node:{title:"The End of 1UP. Long Live 1UP",image:null,path:"/blog/2013/02/22/the-end-of-1-up-long-live-1-up",excerpt:"\n",date:"2013-02-22T00:00:00.000Z",timeToRead:1}}]}}}}}]);